      <p>
        Different objects reflect different amounts and frequencies of light. The amount of light reflected and the
        frequencies of light an object reflects (in the visible range) determine what we see as the object's color.
      </p>

      <ul class="brm-list">
        <li>
          Objects that reflect all—or almost all—light in the visible spectrum appear white—or light-colored—to people.
        </li>
        <li>
          Objects that absorb all—or almost all—light in the visible spectrum appear black—or dark-colored—to people.
        </li>
        <li>
          Objects that only reflect light that has relatively low frequencies on the visible light spectrum appear reddish.
        </li>
        <li>
          Objects that reflect higher-frequency light in the visible light spectrum appear bluish.
        </li>
      </ul>

